  "definition": {
    "en": "Levallorphan Tartrate, when dried, contains not less than 98."
  },
  "appearance": {
    "en": "Levallorphan Tartrate occurs as a white to pale yellow crystalline powder. It is odorless. It is soluble in water and in acetic acid (100), sparingly soluble in ethanol (95), and practically insoluble in diethyl ether."
  },
  "testSpecification": [
    {
      "@type": "IdentificationSpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Identification"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Identification",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Determine the absorption spectrum of a solution of Levallorphan Tartrate in 0.01 mol/L hydrochlo-ric acid TS (1 in 10,000) as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectrophotometry <2.24>, and compare the spectrum with the Reference Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensi-ties of absorption at the same wavelengths. Determine the infrared absorption spectrum of Levallorphan Tartrate, previously dried, as directed in the potassium bromide disk method under Infrared Spectropho-tometry <2.25>, and compare the spectrum with the Refer-ence Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of ab-sorption at the same wave numbers. A solution of Levallorphan Tartrate (1 in 30) re-sponds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> (1) and (2) for tartrate. D Optical rotation <2.49> [a]20: －37.0 – －39.29(after dry-ing, 0.2 g, water, 10 mL, 100 mm). pH <2.54> Dissolve 0.2 g of Levallorphan Tartrate in 20 Each mL of 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid VS ＝ 43.35 mg of C19H25NO.C4H6O6"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "PuritySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Purity"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Purity",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Clarity and color of solution—Dissolve 0.2 g of Levallorphan Tartrate in 10 mL of water: the solution is clear and colorless. Heavy metals <1.07>—Proceed with 1.0 g of Levallor- phan Tartrate according to Method 4, and perform the test. Prepare the control solution with 2.0 mL of Standard Lead Solution (not more than 20 ppm). Related substances—Dissolve 0.20 g of Levallorphan Tartrate in 10 mL of water, and use this solution as the sam-ple solution. Pipet 1 mL of the sample solution, add water to make exactly 100 mL, and use this solution as the standard solution. Perform the test with these solutions as directed under Thin-layer Chromatography <2.03>. Spot 20 mL each of the sample solution and standard solution on a plate of silica gel for thin-layer chromatography. Develop the plate with a mixture of methanol and ammonia TS (200:3) to a distance of about 10 cm, and air-dry the plate. Spray evenly Dragendorff's TS for spraying on the plate: the spots other than the principal spot obtained from the sample solution are not more intense than the spot from the standard solu-tion. Loss on drying <2.41> Not more than 0.5z (1 g, in vacu-um, phosphorus (V) oxide, 809C, 4 hours). Residue on ignition <2.44> Not more than 0.10z (1 g)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "AssaySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Assay"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Assay",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "Weigh accurately about 0.5 g of Levallorphan Tar-trate, previously dried, dissolve in 30 mL of acetic acid (100), and titrate <2.50> with 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid VS (indica-tor: 2 drops of crystal violet TS). Perform a blank determi-nation in the same manner, and make any necessary correc-tion. C19H25NO.C4H6O6: 433.49 17-Allylmorphinan-3-ol monotartrate [71-82-9] Levallorphan Tartrate, when dried, contains not less than 98.5z of levallorphan tartrate (C19H25NO. C4H6O6). Description Levallorphan Tartrate occurs as a white to pale yellow crystalline powder. It is odorless. It is soluble in water and in acetic acid (100), sparingly soluble in ethanol (95), and practically insoluble in diethyl ether. Identification (1) Determine the absorption spectrum of a solution of Levallorphan Tartrate in 0.01 mol/L hydrochlo-ric acid TS (1 in 10,000) as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectrophotometry <2.24>, and compare the spectrum with the Reference Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensi-ties of absorption at the same wavelengths. Determine the infrared absorption spectrum of Levallorphan Tartrate, previously dried, as directed in the potassium bromide disk method under Infrared Spectropho-tometry <2.25>, and compare the spectrum with the Refer-ence Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of ab-sorption at the same wave numbers. A solution of Levallorphan Tartrate (1 in 30) re-sponds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> (1) and (2) for tartrate. D Optical rotation <2.49> [a]20: －37.0 – －39.29(after dry-ing, 0.2 g, water, 10 mL, 100 mm). pH <2.54> Dissolve 0.2 g of Levallorphan Tartrate in 20 Each mL of 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid VS ＝ 43.35 mg of C19H25NO.C4H6O6"
      }
    }
  ],
  "storageConditions": {
    "en": "Containers—Well-closed contain-ers."
  }
}